(1826,'3-703-1',703,3,'When critical details about priority are missing or hidden from view, it becomes harder to anticipate the choices other road users make. Parked vehicles, blind spots and even the landscape can conceal important information, such as traffic signs or approaching hazards. Right-of-way rules establish priority for special vehicles and road users, and when drivers ignore them, they put everyone at risk.',1),(1827,'1-704-1',704,1,'/media/courses/ddt/FTG/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg',1),(1828,'2-704-1',704,2,'Dangerously Negligent',1),(1829,'3-704-1',704,3,'Fail-to-give-way crashes often happen when drivers:\n• Forget or are unfamiliar with the rules.\n• Fail to scan the roadway for signs or traffic.\n• Do not check mirrors and blind spots for hazards.\n• Signal late or not at all.\n• Let distractions impair their judgment and perception.\n• Are rushed or overconfident, leading to dangerous choices on the road.',1),(1830,'1-705-1',705,1,'/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg',1),(1831,'2-705-1',705,2,'Avoid Fail-to-Give-Way Crashes',1),(1832,'3-705-1',705,3,'Common courtesy and the right attitude can go a long way to help you avoid misjudgments that end in a serious crash. This means:\n• Giving way to all moving traffic posing risk of a collision.\n• Signaling intentions properly when changing lanes or turning.\n• Avoiding distractions.\n• Planning your route and leaving early to avoid the compulsion to speed.\n• Giving way to vehicles requiring special priority, such as emergency vehicles.',1),(1833,'28-706-1',706,28,'/media/courses/ddt/FTG/Global/Intro/IMG01.jpg',1),(1834,'6-706-1',706,6,'/media/courses/ddt/FTG/Global/Video/default.mp4',1),(1835,'143-706-1',706,143,'',1),(1836,'144-706-1',706,144,'',1),(1837,'145-706-1',706,145,'',1),(1838,'7-706-1',706,7,'',1),(1839,'8-706-1',706,8,'',1),(1840,'115-706-1',706,115,'',1),(1841,'112-706-1',706,112,'2',1),(1842,'113-706-1',706,113,'2',1),(1843,'111-706-1',706,111,'2',1),(1844,'114-706-1',706,114,'asse