ection, motorists, cyclists and pedestrians all cross paths at different speeds and from different directions in a tight space. The variety of signs, signals and road markings also can be overwhelming and distracting. The resulting confusion is often deadly: At least 1 out of 5 traffic fatalities occurs at an intersection.',1),(1999,'1-771-1',771,1,'/media/courses/ddt/JCT/Global/Slides/IMG03.svg',1),(2000,'2-771-1',771,2,'Intersections Are Misunderstood',1),(2001,'3-771-1',771,3,'A four-way intersection with traffic signals is what many people think of as an intersection, but roundabouts, T-junctions, staggered crossings, driveways meeting roads, and crosswalks are all examples as well. Anywhere two or more roads intersect, the crash risk increases.',1),(2002,'1-772-1',772,1,'/media/courses/ddt/JCT/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg',1),(2003,'2-772-1',772,2,'Uncontrollable Hazards',1),(2004,'3-772-1',772,3,'An intersection’s hazards are often magnified by factors outside a driver’s control. Adverse weather can greatly increase a vehicle’s stopping distance. Parked vehicles, the landscape and roadwork can obscure sightlines, and other road users may act in unexpected or dangerous ways. Up to 50% of collisions with pedestrians and cyclists, the most vulnerable road users, occur at intersections.',1),(2005,'1-773-1',773,1,'/media/courses/ddt/JCT/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg',1),(2006,'2-773-1',773,2,'Common Driver Mistakes',1),(2007,'3-773-1',773,3,'The following driver mistakes are responsible for many common intersection collisions:\n• Running red or yellow lights.\n• Signaling late or not signaling at all.\n• Changing lanes at the last moment or inside the intersection.\n• Forgetting to check for other road users in blind spots.\n',1),(2008,'1-774-1',774,1,'/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg',1),(2009,'2-774-1',774,2,'Navigating Intersections Safely',1),(2010,'3-774-1',774,3,'Here are some essential techniques to reduce the risk when navigating an intersection:\n•  Scan co