ge turning radius often forces them far into an intersection or across two lanes. Many car drivers hit by a truck did not respect the truck’s size and weight.',1),(2370,'1-914-1',914,1,'/media/courses/ddt/LTR/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg',1),(2371,'2-914-1',914,2,'Unpredictable Hazards ',1),(2372,'3-914-1',914,3,'Many of the dangers posed by trucks are out of your control. Truck tires can blow out or their brakes can fail, causing a serious threat for nearby motorists. In bad weather, heavy splash reduces visibility, and air turbulence from a truck can force a nearby car to lose control. \n\nFatigue is another problem for truck drivers. Tiredness is a factor in up to 30% of commercial transport crashes. ',1),(2373,'1-916-1',916,1,'/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg',1),(2374,'2-916-1',916,2,'Techniques to Avoid Collisions ',1),(2375,'3-916-1',916,3,'The best solution to reduce your risk of a collision with a large truck is to avoid them altogether. When you do encounter a large truck on the road, making the truck driver aware of your presence will help keep both of you safe. This means:\n• Signaling during lane changes. \n• Giving trucks room to complete their maneuvers.\n• Checking mirrors and blind spots before passing a truck.\n• Staying out of a truck’s blind spots.',1),(2376,'1-915-1',915,1,'/media/courses/ddt/LTR/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg',1),(2377,'2-915-1',915,2,'Who Is at Fault?',1),(2378,'3-915-1',915,3,'In car-truck collisions, it is often the driver of the smaller vehicle who makes the mistake, such as improper lane changes and disrespecting a truck’s large size and blind spots. Car drivers are responsible for the majority of car-truck crashes.   ',1),(2379,'12-917-1',917,12,'Trucks Stop Slower',1),(2380,'14-917-1',917,14,'Traveling at 80 km/h, some large trucks take up to 50% longer to stop than a car.',1),(2381,'13-917-1',917,13,'/media/courses/ddt/LTR/Global/Stats/IMG01.svg',1),(2382,'35-917-1',917,35,'',1),(2383,'6-918-1',918,6,'/media/courses/ddt/L