,1189,1,'/media/courses/ddt/SPD/Global/Slides/IMG03.svg',1),(3088,'2-1189-1',1189,2,'The Impact of Speeding',1),(3089,'3-1189-1',1189,3,'In the event of a collision, the vehicle and the people inside absorb its full force. In a crash at 90 km/h, the impact on a human body is equivalent to falling from the first floor of a building, while the impact of a crash at 120 km/h is like falling from the ninth floor.',1),(3090,'1-1190-1',1190,1,'/media/courses/ddt/SPD/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg',1),(3091,'2-1190-1',1190,2,'Gains vs. Costs',1),(3092,'3-1190-1',1190,3,'Drivers who increase their average speed from 95 km/h to 110 km/h save only a few seconds per kilometer. Compare that to what could cost more, such as some of the potential consequences of speeding in Asia:\n• Decreased stopping power.\n• Fines and penalty points.\n• Possible license suspension or jail time.\n• Injury or death.  \n',1),(3093,'1-1191-1',1191,1,'/media/courses/ddt/SPD/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg',1),(3094,'2-1191-1',1191,2,'Mistakes Add Up',1),(3095,'3-1191-1',1191,3,'Tired or distracted drivers may speed unconsciously, while aggressive motorists choose to speed, leading to tailgating, weaving through traffic, and running red lights. Any of these drivers can be unaware of the effect speed has on stopping distance. For example, a car can take twice as long to stop at 50 km/h compared to 30 km/h, unless a crash stops the driver first.',1),(3096,'1-1192-1',1192,1,'/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg',1),(3097,'2-1192-1',1192,2,'Speed Limits Save Lives',1),(3098,'3-1192-1',1192,3,'Most roads are not designed for speeds above the posted limit. Maximum speeds are set to help ensure motorists’ safety based on a road’s design and environment. This is why speed limits are not guidelines; they are the law. Ultimately, obeying them helps to keep you, your passengers and the people around you safe.',1),(3099,'12-1193-1',1193,12,'Unnecessary Losses',1),(3100,'14-1193-1',1193,14,'Excess or inappropriate speed i