strict a driver’s view of the road. Besides reducing visibility, rain can cause a vehicle to hydroplane, meaning the tires lose contact with the road surface and glide on water. Large amounts of water, such as a flooded road, diminish the effectiveness of brakes.',1),(3270,'1-1259-1',1259,1,'/media/courses/ddt/WEA/Global/Slides/IMG04.svg',1),(3271,'2-1259-1',1259,2,'Veiled Threats',1),(3272,'3-1259-1',1259,3,'Even when the sky is clear, natural hazards can create significant dangers for drivers. At some angles, bright sunshine can temporarily blind motorists in traffic. High winds restrict steering ability and can push vehicles off course, particularly large trucks. Crosswinds also create air turbulence when entering or leaving tunnels or other covered areas. Another problem is heat, which can make drivers tired or take a heavy toll on vehicles’ engines. ',1),(3273,'1-1260-1',1260,1,'/media/courses/ddt/WEA/Global/Slides/IMG05.svg',1),(3274,'2-1260-1',1260,2,'Dangerous Neglect',1),(3275,'3-1260-1',1260,3,'Dangerous weather exposes drivers to hazards that are out of their control, yet some refuse to adjust to the conditions despite the risk. These motorists drive too fast, leave insufficient room around other vehicles, or fail to prepare their vehicles for changes in season. Poor choices make it difficult to drive safely in adverse conditions, and they can leave drivers stranded, injured in a crash or worse. ',1),(3276,'1-1261-1',1261,1,'/media/courses/ddt/global/slides/IMG06.svg',1),(3277,'2-1261-1',1261,2,'Prepare for the Worst',1),(3278,'3-1261-1',1261,3,'It is best to avoid traveling in bad weather altogether. If you must head out, listen to weather reports, observe conditions around you continuously, and bring an emergency kit that includes:\n• Non-perishable food and bottled water.\n• Reflective clothing.\n• A blanket and extra pair of shoes.\n• A first-aid kit and seatbelt cutter.\n• Road maps.\n• Antifreeze liquid and jumper cables.\n• Warning triangles, warni